Bootstrapping

Yuxuan Chen

11/28/2021

Repeated sampling: iterative tool - what is the variance of estimated intercepts and slopes in repeated different samples?

Bootstrap works well when assumptions are not met and met! (no need to assume normal distribution)

library(tidyverse)
library(p8105.datasets)
library(modelr)

knitr::opts_chunk$set(
  fig.width = 8,
  fig.asp = .6,
  out.width = "90%"
)

theme_set(theme_minimal() + theme(legend.position = "bottom"))

options(
  ggplot2.continuous.colour = "viridis", 
  ggplot2.continuous.fill = "viridis"
)

scale_colour_discrete = scale_colour_viridis_d
scale_fill_discrete = scale_fill_viridis_d

set.seed(1)
n_samp = 250

sim_df_const = 
  tibble(
    x = rnorm(n_samp, 1, 1),
    error = rnorm(n_samp, 0, 1),
    y = 2 + 3 * x + error
  )

sim_df_nonconst = sim_df_const %>% 
  mutate(
  error = error * .75 * x,
  y = 2 + 3 * x + error
)

plot the datasets

sim_df_const %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

sim_df_nonconst %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

# assume constant residual variance

Drawing one bootstrap sample

  1. generating boot samples
# this function: sets dataframe as the argument, and return a sample from that dataframe drawn with replacement.

boot_sample = function(df) {
  sample_frac(df, replace = TRUE) %>%  # replace with same sample sizes
    arrange(x) # arrange data
}

check function:

boot_sample(sim_df_nonconst) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.3) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  ylim(-5, 16)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

boot_sample(sim_df_nonconst) %>% 
  lm(y ~ x, data = .) %>% 
  broom::tidy()
## # A tibble: 2  5
##   term        estimate std.error statistic   p.value
##   <chr>          <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept)     1.90    0.0982      19.3 2.45e- 51
## 2 x               3.14    0.0688      45.6 1.18e-122

many samples and analysis

  1. Drawing many bootstrap samples
boot_straps = 
  tibble(
    strap_number = 1:1000,
    strap_sample = rerun(1000, boot_sample(sim_df_nonconst))
  )

# check 1st dataframe:
## boot_straps %>% pull(strap_sample) %>% .[[1]]
  1. Run analysis on it:
boot_results = 
  boot_straps %>% 
  mutate(
    models = map(strap_sample, ~lm(y ~ x, data = .x)),
    results = map(models, broom::tidy)
  ) %>% 
  select(strap_number, results) %>% 
  unnest(results)

boot_results

  1. distribution of estimated slopes and intercepts
boot_results %>% 
  group_by(term) %>% 
  summarize(
    mean_est = mean(estimate),
    sd_est = sd(estimate)
  )
## # A tibble: 2  3
##   term        mean_est sd_est
##   <chr>          <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept)     1.93 0.0748
## 2 x               3.11 0.101
boot_results %>% 
  filter(term == "x") %>%  # only focus on intercept
  ggplot(aes(x = estimate)) +
  geom_density()

  1. bootstrap Confidence Interval:
boot_results %>% 
  group_by(term) %>% 
  summarize(
    ci_lower = quantile(estimate, 0.025),
    ci_upper = quantile(estimate, 0.975),
  )
## # A tibble: 2  3
##   term        ci_lower ci_upper
##   <chr>          <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept)     1.79     2.08
## 2 x               2.91     3.31

Boptstrap using modelr

simplify:

# similar than previous results

sim_df_nonconst %>% 
  bootstrap(1000, id = "strap_number") %>% 
  mutate(
    models = map(.x = strap, ~lm(y ~ x, data = .x)),
    results = map(models, broom::tidy)
  ) %>% 
  select(strap_number, results) %>% 
  unnest(results) %>% 
  group_by(term) %>% 
  summarize(mean_est = mean(estimate),
    sd_est = sd(estimate)
  )
## # A tibble: 2  3
##   term        mean_est sd_est
##   <chr>          <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept)     1.93 0.0762
## 2 x               3.11 0.104
  • Does bootstrap also work well when assumptions met? Yes!

revisit nyc airbnb

data("nyc_airbnb")

nyc_airbnb = 
  nyc_airbnb %>% 
  mutate(stars = review_scores_location / 2) %>% 
  rename(
    borough = neighbourhood_group,
    neighborhood = neighbourhood) %>% 
  filter(borough != "Staten Island") %>% 
  select(price, stars, borough, neighborhood, room_type)
nyc_airbnb %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = stars, y = price)) +
  geom_point()
## Warning: Removed 9962 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

airbnb_boot_results = 
  nyc_airbnb %>% 
  filter(borough == "Manhattan") %>% 
  drop_na(stars) %>% 
  bootstrap(1000, id = "strap_number") %>% 
  mutate(
    models = map(.x = strap, ~lm(price ~ stars, data = .x)),
    results = map(models, broom::tidy)
  ) %>% 
  select(strap_number, results) %>% 
  unnest(results)

airbnb_boot_results %>% 
  group_by(term) %>% 
  summarize(mean_est = mean(estimate),
    sd_est = sd(estimate)
  )
## # A tibble: 2  3
##   term        mean_est sd_est
##   <chr>          <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept)    -35.0  31.3 
## 2 stars           43.4   6.34
